  "title": "Prevalencia de Lactancia Materna Exclusiva en el Servicio de Neonatología de un Hospital Pediátrico de Sonora, México",
  "abstract": "Background: Breastfeeding (BF) is the optimal nutrition for premature and sick infants hospitalized at neonatal care units, because of its association with a reduction of morbidity and mortality rates during and after hospitalization. By estimating prevalence of exclusive breastfeeding (EBF) can help to delineate strategies to foster it s practice. Objective: To determine prevalence of EBF in a neonatal care unit of a public pediatric hospital. Methods: We carried out a cross-sectional design on a non-probabilistic sample of 177 hospitalized infants throughout the period of May to October 2014. Results: The prevalence of EBF was 3.4%. The mixed feeding had the highest (71.8%) prevalence, while 24.9% received Prevalencia de Lactancia Materna Exclusiva en el Servicio de Neonatologia de un Hospital Pediatrico de Sonora, Mexico. Paulina Blanco-Cervantes* Elizabeth Hoyos-Loya* Gerardo Alvarez-Hernandez** Carlos Arturo Ramirez-Rodriguez*** * Lic. en Ciencias Nutricionales, Universidad de Sonora. ** Departamento de Medicina y Ciencias de la Salud. Universidad de Sonora. *** Jefe del Servicio de Neonatologia del HIES. Correspondencia: Dr. Gerardo Alvarez Hernandez. galvarez@guayacan.uson.mx, Blvd. Luis Donaldo Colosi o SN, Col. Centro, Hermosil lo, Sonora, C.P. 83000, Tel. (662) 112-60-80. 3 Bol Clin Hosp Infant Edo Son 2015; 32(1): 3-9",
